text=:Category: TypologyOfPhoneticContrasts%0a:Expansion: Why English Speakers struggle to produce front rounded vowels%0a:Author: sebastiang%0a:Original: [[Articles.FrontRoundedVowelsComparingEnglishAndMandarin|FrontRoundedVowelsComparingEnglishAndMandarin]] %0a:OriginalAuthor: [[Profiles.angelaw|angelaw]]%0a:Section: F%0a:Completed: 27.02.2021 - 09:56%0a:Status: complete%0a%0a(:foxform Site.FoxForms#gradeitem:)%0a(:foxform Site.FoxForms#gradingcomment:)%0a%0a%0a%25red%25 '''Grading History'''%0a%0a[[#history]]%0a#foxbegin 210512-124717-375580#%0a* [-12.05.2021 - 05:47-] || TA_mason marked as complete%0a#foxend 210512-124717-375580#%0a[[#historyend]]%0a%0a%25red%25 '''Comments to student'''%0a%0a[[#comments]]%0a%0a[[#commentsend]]%0a%0a----%0a----%0a!!%0a%0a%0a----%0a[[#content]]%0a%0aThis expansion deals with how the feature value (front rounded vowels) presents a special challenge to speech synthesis.%0a%0aIn most languages, front vowels are usually unrounded while back and mid/high vowels are usually rounded. This is because lip rounding reinforces the "low pitched acoustic overtones that are characteristic of back and non-low vowels. Specifically, rounding and protruding the lips lowers the frequencies produced by the glottal source in the oral tract. This adds to the lowering effect caused by moving the tongue body back.%0a%0aThe fact that we associate back and non-low vowels with roundness and front high vowels with unroundness may be the reason why American English speakers find it difficult to produce rounded front vowels. Languages such as Mandarin which are more flexible with rounding have greater variety in vowel production. %0a%0ahttps://wals.info/chapter/11%0a%0a[[#contentends]]%0a----%0a(:Category:)%0a#foxbegin 210512-000935-408950#%0a!!Backup interface%0a(:foxform Site.FoxForms#gradeExpansion:)%0a#foxend 210512-000935-408950#%0a(:GradedBy: TA_mason:)
